# Signal Lab — Project Context

## Project goal
Signal Lab is an observability playground.

The system simulates backend scenarios and makes them visible through:
- Prometheus metrics
- Loki logs
- Grafana dashboards
- optional database persistence through Prisma

## Main user flow
The user triggers a scenario.
The backend runs the scenario and produces:
- logs
- metrics
- optional storage writes

The system must remain observable even when the database is unavailable.

## Current stack
- Backend: NestJS + TypeScript
- Metrics: prom-client
- Persistence: Prisma + PostgreSQL
- Observability: Prometheus, Loki, Promtail, Grafana
- Infra: Docker Compose
- AI layer: Cursor rules, skills, commands, hooks

## Current backend behavior
Implemented scenario types:
- test_scenario
- slow_success
- system_error

Implemented endpoints:
- GET /health
- GET /metrics
- GET /scenarios
- POST /scenarios

## Important engineering intent
This project prioritizes observability over storage reliability.

That means:
- metrics must still be emitted even if Prisma fails
- logs must still be written even if Prisma fails
- scenario execution should continue when storage fails, unless the request is explicitly storage-dependent
- storage-dependent reads may return ServiceUnavailable

## Existing observability behavior
- custom metric: scenario_runs_total
- scenario execution emits statuses such as started, completed, error
- scenario logs must remain structured and meaningful
- Grafana reads Prometheus and Loki through provisioned datasources

## AI layer intent
Cursor should act as a scoped implementation assistant.
Cursor must preserve working observability behavior and avoid destructive refactors.